# FABRIC OS — PHASE 0: BARE METAL BOOT
## Complete Implementation Specification

**Prerequisite:** Read `README.md` in this directory for full project context.
**Goal:** Boot Fabric OS in QEMU, set up memory management, print to serial.
**Language:** Rust (nightly, no_std)
**Bootloader:** Limine (v8.x)
**Test VM:** QEMU x86_64
**Done When:** Boots in QEMU, detects physical memory, allocates/frees pages, maps virtual memory, has a working kernel heap, prints to serial console, passes OCRB memory stress gate.

---

## PART 1: DEVELOPMENT ENVIRONMENT SETUP

### 1.1 — Platform Decision

**Recommended: WSL2 (Ubuntu 22.04+) on Windows**

OS development tooling is Linux-native. WSL2 gives you:
- Native Linux build environment
- QEMU runs natively (no Windows path headaches)
- All cross-compilation tools work out of the box
- Can still edit code from Windows (VS Code + WSL remote)

Alternative: Native Windows with MSYS2/Git Bash works but you'll fight path issues. WSL2 is the right call.

### 1.2 — Install WSL2 (if not already)

```bash
# From Windows PowerShell (admin):
wsl --install -d Ubuntu-22.04

# After install, open Ubuntu terminal and update:
sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y
```

### 1.3 — Install Rust Nightly

```bash
# Install rustup
curl --proto '=https' --tlsv1.2 -sSf https://sh.rustup.rs | sh

# Source the environment
source ~/.cargo/env

# Install nightly toolchain
rustup toolchain install nightly

# Set nightly as default for this project (we'll do this per-project later)
# But globally for now:
rustup default nightly

# Add required components
rustup component add rust-src          # Source code for core/alloc (needed for build-std)
rustup component add llvm-tools-preview # For objcopy, objdump, etc.

# Verify
rustc --version  # Should show nightly-YYYY-MM-DD
cargo --version
```

### 1.4 — Install QEMU

```bash
# Ubuntu/WSL2:
sudo apt install qemu-system-x86 -y

# Verify
qemu-system-x86_64 --version
```

### 1.5 — Install OVMF (UEFI Firmware for QEMU)

```bash
sudo apt install ovmf -y

# OVMF firmware will be at: /usr/share/OVMF/OVMF_CODE.fd
# Verify it exists:
ls -la /usr/share/OVMF/OVMF_CODE.fd
```

### 1.6 — Install Build Utilities

```bash
sudo apt install -y \
  build-essential \
  nasm \
  xorriso \
  mtools \
  git \
  curl \
  gdb
```

### 1.7 — Install Limine Bootloader

```bash
# Clone Limine v8.x (latest stable)
git clone https://github.com/limine-bootloader/limine.git --branch=v8.x-binary --depth=1 ~/limine

# Build the limine utility
cd ~/limine
make

# Verify
ls -la limine  # Should see the `limine` binary
```

### 1.8 — Environment Verification Checklist

Run each of these. All must succeed before proceeding:

```bash
rustc +nightly --version          # nightly-2026-XX-XX or later
cargo +nightly --version          # same date
rustup component list --installed | grep rust-src      # rust-src installed
rustup component list --installed | grep llvm-tools    # llvm-tools installed
qemu-system-x86_64 --version     # QEMU 6.x or later
ls /usr/share/OVMF/OVMF_CODE.fd  # OVMF exists
ls ~/limine/limine                # Limine binary exists
nasm --version                    # NASM assembler
xorriso --version                 # ISO creation tool
```

**If all 8 checks pass, the environment is ready.**

